# 3. Terminology and Vocabulary Rules

RULE CV1 — Use domain-specific language, not generic software terms

Labels and messages must use the vocabulary of the business domain, not internal system terms, programmer jargon, or generic software language.

What to look for:
- Do labels use terms the user says out loud in their daily work?
- Are database or API names exposed to the user (entity, payload, object, resource, record)?
- Are generic terms used where specific terms exist ("item" instead of "claim", "thing" instead of "transaction")?

Good: "Dispute Case", "Settlement Amount", "Clearing Date", "Beneficiary Account"
Bad: "Entity", "Object", "Resource", "Payload", "Data Element", "Record"

Good: "Submit for Compliance Review"
Bad: "Execute Process"

Severity: Major

RULE CV2 — Use one consistent term per concept throughout the application

When the same concept is called different things on different screens, users waste time determining if they're the same thing.

What to look for:
- Is the same entity called the same thing everywhere (not "Customer" on one screen, "Client" on another, "Account Holder" on a third)?
- Are action verbs consistent (not "Save" on one screen and "Update" on another for the same operation)?
- Are status labels consistent (not "Pending" on one screen and "Awaiting Review" on another for the same state)?
- Is there evidence of a shared vocabulary or glossary being followed?

How to check: Look for every instance where a core business concept appears and verify the exact term is identical.

Good: "Merchant" is used everywhere — sidebar, tables, forms, headers, notifications.
Bad: "Merchant" on the list page, "Vendor" on the detail page, "Seller" in notifications, "MER" in the status bar.

Severity: Major

RULE CV3 — Define abbreviations and acronyms on first use

What to look for:
- Are abbreviations defined in a tooltip or parenthetical on first use?
- Are only widely understood abbreviations used without definition?
- Is a glossary accessible from the application?

Good: "KYC (Know Your Customer) Review" with a tooltip on "KYC" explaining the term.
Bad: "FDR-KYB-AML Review" with no expansion of any acronym.

Severity: Minor — Major if abbreviations are used for decision-critical fields.

RULE CV4 — Units and formats must be explicit

What to look for:
- Are currency labels included ("Amount (USD)" not just "Amount")?
- Are date formats explicit or unambiguous ("Mar 8, 2026" not "03/08/26")?
- Are time zones indicated where relevant ("Submitted: Mar 8, 2026, 14:32 EST")?
- Are measurement units included ("Duration (days)", "File Size (MB)")?

Good: "Settlement Amount (USD): $12,450.00" and "Filing Date: Mar 8, 2026"
Bad: "Amount: 12450" and "Date: 03/08/26"

Severity: Major — ambiguous units can cause operational errors (wrong currency, wrong date interpretation).

